A sole source HUBZone small business set-aside is justified under 10 USC 2304(c)(5), FAR 6.302-5, authorized or required by statute.

FAR Part 19.1306(a) specify when a sole source HUBZone small business set-aside is appropriate. This acquisition meets those circumstances, as follows:
a. The contracting officer does not have a reasonable expectation that offers would be received from two or more HUBZone small business concerns; Market research identified DH Technologies, LLC as the only HUBZone small business authorized distributor for these items;
b. The anticipated price of the contract, including options, will not exceed $6.5 million for a requirement within the NAICS codes for manufacturing or $4.5 million for a requirement, within any other NAICS code; the applicable NAICS code is 541519 so the $4.5 million limitation applies. As stated above, the estimated dollar value is $532,194 for the base year;
c. This is a new requirement that is not currently being performed by an 8(a) participant under the provisions of FAR subpart 19.8. No performance by an equal 8(a) participant was identified during market research;
d. The HUBZone small business concern has been determined to be a responsible contractor with respect to performance, DH Technologies, LLC has a history of successful performance on previous contracts for these items.

The Contractor shall include a Transition-In Plan that shall identify how the Offeror will coordinate with the prior Contractor and Government personnel to transfer knowledge regarding the following:
• Project management processes;
• Points of contact;
• Location of technical and project management documentation;
• Sharing of documentation of in-progress tasks/activities;
• Key personnel responsibilities;
• Schedules and milestones;
• Approach to developing a cross-walk from the existing Fabric to the one being developed under this contract;
• Provide all licensees support to ensure continuity with the new Fabric developed at the start of this contract compared to the end of the prior contract (i.e., the previous version of the Fabric); and
• Actions required of the Government.

The Offeror shall include a Transition-Out Plan that shall identify how the Offeror will coordinate with the incoming Contractor and Government personnel to transfer knowledge regarding the following:
• Project management processes;
• Points of contact;
• Location of technical and project management documentation;
• Sharing of documentation of in-progress tasks/activities;
• Key personnel responsibilities;
• Schedules and milestones;
• License terms and restrictions (including access to and use of the Fabric developed under this contract in transition-out to ensure continuity with the following contract with crosswalk between the Fabric at the end of this contract and the next Fabric of the following contract. FCC is open to approaches such as third-party implementing crosswalk mapping methodologies/algorithms provided by Offeror; and
• Actions required of the Government.

The Contractor shall:

Implement an incremental development approach, using sprints to develop the Technical Publications and shall include incremental reviews. The Contractor shall conduct Validation/Verification events with Government reviewers at the agreed upon development milestones and adjudicate Government comments in accordance with TMMP (E0005-AC-HBK-010/TMMP).

Design, deliver and maintain the LOG IT capability for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD) across the LOG IT portfolio.

Deliver software components and interfaces using proven software development or software configuration/integration methodology; and

Perform development activities, including but not limited to:
Environment, database, reports, and interface development;
COTS and GOTS software configuration, application migration, and integration;
Components, interfaces, and data migration and exchanges to meet functional and system requirements;
Testing of teaming partner, subcontractor, and other contractor provided products and services;
Technology refresh and software update efforts;
Standardization of processes and procedures by which the design is transitioned into a deliverable product or service;
Software customization, if determined necessary by the Government; and
Automated Test Scripts.

52.219-14 Limitations on Subcontracting (Oct 2022)

(a) This clause does not apply to the unrestricted portion of a partial set-aside.
(b) Definition. Similarly situated entity, as used in this clause, means a first-tier subcontractor, including an independent contractor, that-
(1) Has the same small business program status as that which qualified the prime contractor for the award (e.g., for a small business set-aside contract, any small business concern, without regard to its socioeconomic status); and
(2) Is considered small for the size standard under the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code the prime contractor assigned to the subcontract.
(c) Applicability. This clause applies only to-
(1) Contracts that have been set aside for any of the small business concerns identified in 19.000(a)(3);
(2) Part or parts of a multiple-award contract that have been set aside for any of the small business concerns identified in 19.000(a)(3);
(3) Contracts that have been awarded on a sole-source basis in accordance with subparts 19.8, 19.13, 19.14, and 19.15;
(6) Contracts using the HUBZone price evaluation preference to award to a HUBZone small business concern unless the concern waived the evaluation preference.

Phase 2: Solution Presentation/Pitch

Down selected offerors will be invited to present their solutions to the Government and to participate in a live demonstration. The presentation shall include:

Detailed technical and business viability of the solution

Proposed schedule and milestones

Anticipated data rights assertions

Explanation of Data Rights

Rough Order of Magnitude (ROM) pricing: Estimated cost and payment terms.

7.2. Participation in the live demonstration in a relevant environment will be coordinated by the Government.

Phase 2: Presentation/Pitch Evaluation

Individual presentations/pitches will be evaluated against the evaluation criteria below and not against any other presentations/pitches. Presentation/pitch submissions will be valid for 120 days after pitch evaluation. The government will aim to complete evaluation of presentation/pitches within 30 calendar days of the presentation/pitch. After completing the evaluation of presentation/pitch submissions, the government will notify the company that: they may submit a Full Proposal for evaluation in Phase 3; or their proposed concept/technology/solution is not of continued interest to the Government, and they will not be required to submit a Full Proposal and advance to Phase 3.

Presentation/Pitch evaluation criteria are listed in order of importance from top to bottom. Presentation/pitches shall be evaluated/scored on the following factors:

Level of relevancy of the solution in addressing the A-COP with a commercially available product and/or process;

The technical merit of the proposed solution adequately addressed the A-COP and demonstrated feasibility for the Government to pursue the proposed solution;

Level of uniqueness, and/or innovative approach to solve the Government's need;

Level of technical risk/maturity;

Level of risk placed with the proposed ROM;

Level of risk in the proposed milestone schedule and its ability to meet the A-COP requirement within a relevant time period;

Level of risk in the company's viability and business solution; and

Level of potential risk in anticipated IP and data rights assertions
